NYC Taxi Fare Prediction¶

Tomoya Tokunaga (October 2018)¶

This notebook I created for New York City Taxi Fare Prediction from Kaggle Competition.
The original datasets were downloadable from the link above.

def plot_on_nyc_map(data, coordinate):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,12))
    # this is a map for pickup locations
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
    ax1 = Basemap(projection='merc', 
        llcrnrlat = coordinate[0], 
        urcrnrlat = coordinate[1], 
        llcrnrlon = coordinate[2], 
        urcrnrlon = coordinate[3],
        resolution='h'
    )
    ax1.fillcontinents(color='#F2EFE9')
    ax1.drawcoastlines()
    ax1.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#AAD3DF')
    pickup_lon = train["pickup_longitude"].tolist()
    pickup_lat = train['pickup_latitude'].tolist()
    ax1.scatter(pickup_lon, pickup_lat, s=4, zorder=2, latlon=True, color="#FF4500", alpha=0.4)
    plt.title("Pickup Locations")

    # this is a map for dropoff locations
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
    ax2 = Basemap(
        projection='merc', 
        llcrnrlat = coordinate[0], 
        urcrnrlat = coordinate[1], 
        llcrnrlon = coordinate[2], 
        urcrnrlon = coordinate[3],
        resolution='h'
    )
    ax2.fillcontinents(color='#F2EFE9')
    ax2.drawcoastlines()
    ax2.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#AAD3DF')
    dropoff_lon = train["dropoff_longitude"].tolist()
    dropoff_lat = train['dropoff_latitude'].tolist()
    ax2.scatter(dropoff_lon, dropoff_lat, s=4, zorder=2, latlon=True, color="#FF4500", alpha=0.4)

    plt.title("Dropoff Locations")
    plt.show()

The scatter plots above tells that some pickup/ dropoff locations are on the ocean. This has to be regarded as noise. So, the next step is removing those invalid plots from the dataset. A Basemap method called is_land(x, y) checks if a coordinate (x, y) is on the land. By removing the points whose coordinates is returned False by is_land(x, y), we can have much cleaner dataset.

Remove Points under the Sea¶

In [10]:
# This function is based on plot_on_nyc_map and added some codes to filter points on the ocean out.
def plot_on_nyc_map_2(data, coordinate):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,12))
    # this is a map for pickup locations
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
    ax1 = Basemap(projection='merc', 
        llcrnrlat = coordinate[0], 
        urcrnrlat = coordinate[1], 
        llcrnrlon = coordinate[2], 
        urcrnrlon = coordinate[3],
        resolution='h'
    )
    ax1.fillcontinents(color='#F2EFE9')
    ax1.drawcoastlines()
    ax1.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#AAD3DF')
    # this is a map for pickup locations    
    pickup_lon = data["pickup_longitude"]
    pickup_lat = data["pickup_latitude"]
    for i in range(len(pickup_lon)):
        xpt, ypt = ax1(pickup_lon[i], pickup_lat[i])
        if ax1.is_land(xpt, ypt) == False:
            data = data.drop([i])
    
    data = data.reset_index(drop=True)
    pickup_lon = data["pickup_longitude"].tolist()
    pickup_lat = data['pickup_latitude'].tolist()
    ax1.scatter(pickup_lon, pickup_lat, s=4, zorder=2, latlon=True, color="#FF4500", alpha=0.4)
    plt.title("Pickup Locations")

    # this is a map for dropoff locations
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
    ax2 = Basemap(
        projection='merc', 
        llcrnrlat = coordinate[0], 
        urcrnrlat = coordinate[1], 
        llcrnrlon = coordinate[2], 
        urcrnrlon = coordinate[3],
        resolution='h'
    )
    ax2.fillcontinents(color='#F2EFE9')
    ax2.drawcoastlines()
    ax2.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#AAD3DF')
    # removing locations on the ocean
    dropoff_lon = data["dropoff_longitude"]
    dropoff_lat = data["dropoff_latitude"]
    for i in range(len(dropoff_lon)):
        xpt, ypt = ax2(dropoff_lon[i], dropoff_lat[i])
        if ax2.is_land(xpt, ypt) == False:
            data = data.drop([i])
    
    data = data.reset_index(drop=True)
    dropoff_lon = data["dropoff_longitude"].tolist()
    dropoff_lat = data['dropoff_latitude'].tolist()
    ax2.scatter(dropoff_lon, dropoff_lat, s=4, zorder=2, latlon=True, color="#FF4500", alpha=0.4)

    plt.title("Dropoff Locations")
    plt.show()
    
    return data

Define "distance" Column¶

The next step is creating a new column which is related to the trip distance between pickup and dropoff locations because it's very reasonable that fare amount is dependent on how long a customer rides.

We're going to use the Pythagorean theorem to find out approximate trip distance.
Let's suppose:

A = Pickup Location
B = Dropoff Location
C = Trip Distance

Then,

$$C = \sqrt{A^2 + B^2}$$

We're going to apply this formula to both latitudu and longitude respectively.

In [13]:
# This function calculates distance of two points using the Pythagorian theorem
def distance_calc(data):
    lat_dis = abs(data["dropoff_latitude"]-data["pickup_latitude"])
    lon_dis = abs(data["dropoff_longitude"]-data["pickup_longitude"])
    return np.sqrt(lat_dis**2 + lon_dis**2)

train['distance'] = distance_calc(train)
test['distance'] = distance_calc(test)
train.head(10)

Find Outliers¶

We have already cleaned our training dataset quite well, but we still have some room for improvement. As we can see from the statistics shown right above this cell, fare_amount column seems to have the upper outliers. Removing outliers can make our predictions more accurate.

We're going to identify outliers using the following formula from a Statistics textbook:
Let
$$z = \frac{x - \bar{x}}{\sigma}$$
Then, outlier x is:
$$\{x := x\in\mathbb{R}|z<-3, 3<x\}$$

In [16]:
z = (cleaned_train - cleaned_train.mean())/cleaned_train.std()
z = z[(z > -3) & (z < 3)]
refined_train = z*cleaned_train.std() + cleaned_train.mean()
refined_train = refined_train.dropna(axis=0)
refined_train.describe()

Two scatter plots shown above tell us that distance and fare amounts have stronger correlation by removing outliers. Although it seems that removing outliers is always good for more accurate prediction, it could occur we miss some significant data. So we procced creating our machine learning model using both data and decide which we use based on their RMSE(Root Mean Square Error).

Machine Learning Model¶

For this taxi fare price predicion, we're going to use linear regression model using a scikit-learn package, LinearRegression.

cleaned_train_predictions = cleaned_lr.predict(cleaned_train[['distance']])
cleaned_test_predictions = cleaned_lr.predict(test[['distance']])
